Tonight was a big event in the travel industry. It was Travel Weekly’s Reader’s Choice Awards. I had been invited by Delta Vacations a long time ago, and was looking forward to it all year, especially as I was going through my cancer treatment. It may not make sense to you, but putting on some sequins and jewelry sure feels nice when you’ve been dealing with chemo and radiation and hospital visits. But, it wasn’t just getting dolled up and going out. It was seeing my friends, colleagues, and people who I just adore in my industry. I am so grateful that so many of them followed my journey to this point, and told me so when I saw them tonight. In fact, so many people shared their own journey because of it. My heart is very full tonight for so many reasons. #TWRCA
Last flight of the year. I am going home to my family to love and harass them in equal amounts.
A lot of you are entertaining this week and the next. If you need some inspiration, here’s some of my own party recipes.

“You can choose to be sad or you can choose joy.” 

This is from a book by someone who entered my life with a backdrop of fireworks, Jodi Bainter. She wrote it about her brave son, Jake, and her family after a lawn mower accident changed their lives forever. The book is comprised of her personal and raw journal entries over the four years following the incident. 

I did not know this part of Jodi’s life until I ran into her last week, and she inquired about my journey. I shared how this dreadful thing called cancer connected to me to a world and a purpose that I could have never imagined for myself. 

She could relate, and wrote a book about it. 

I ordered her book “Make It Morning” from Amazon immediately. (You should too.)

As I read Jodi’s book, I landed on this chapter labeled, “Choose Joy.” Now, the word “joy” has always been one of the most intriguing words in my opinion. It’s so small, but so massive at the same time. It is a thought. It is something you can experience. It is something you can give. Sometimes, I think you can even touch it. 

Joy fascinates me. 

In this chapter, Jodi talks about how one chooses their attitude. It doesn’t mean that the pain, fear, or anger goes away. It just means that you can reconfigure your response. And, by doing so, you can let light, love, and the universe in. That may change more than the way you feel. Sometimes it can change the world around you. 

While I have been dealing with being ill this year, and ultimately the cancer diagnosis and subsequent treatment, I was surrounded by joy. However, I didn’t choose it. You guys forced that joy on me. 

I had a few wobbles, but there you were with words of encouragement or sending positive energy my way that caused a visceral reaction. You joyed the wobbles away. 

While the choice to choose joy is something that I will be more conscious of in the future, I really appreciate the fact that you didn’t give me a choice. I will never be able to truly display my gratitude. 

Joy. To. The. World. 

And buy Jodi Bainter’s
book.

A little over a year ago on Norwegian’s Prima, I was navigating the news that I had cancer by myself. 

Last night, on her sister ship, Norwegian’s Viva, I got engaged to my fella amongst friends. (Viva means “live,” by the way.) 

I was awkward, but effective as we sailed along Croatia, and he said yes. 

A special thank you to my witnesses: Jillian, Danny, Steve, Alina, Maria, and Mary. If they hadn’t all been there, it wouldn’t have happened when it did for many reasons.

To the crew onboard the Viva, I love you all, but I cannot eat another piece of cake. How about celebratory high fives?

I was so happy to be amongst so many friends during this one moment in time. 

(Note: I had cancer. Cancer is gone.
